-- PASSAGE 7: Photosynthesis (Questions 61-70)
('reading', NULL, 61, 'Passage 7:\n\nPhotosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize nutrients from carbon dioxide and water. This process is fundamental to life on Earth, as it produces oxygen as a byproduct and forms the base of most food chains. Photosynthesis occurs primarily in the leaves of plants, specifically in structures called chloroplasts that contain the green pigment chlorophyll.\n\nThe process of photosynthesis can be divided into two main stages: the light-dependent reactions and the light-independent reactions, also known as the Calvin cycle. During the light-dependent reactions, which occur in the thylakoid membranes of chloroplasts, light energy is absorbed by chlorophyll and converted into chemical energy in the form of ATP and NADPH. These energy-rich molecules are then used in the Calvin cycle to convert carbon dioxide into glucose.\n\nThe rate of photosynthesis is influenced by several environmental factors. Light intensity, carbon dioxide concentration, and temperature all play crucial roles. When light intensity increases, the rate of photosynthesis generally increases until a saturation point is reached. Similarly, higher carbon dioxide concentrations typically enhance photosynthetic rates, though this effect also has limits.\n\nWhat is the main purpose of the passage?', 'To describe the discovery of photosynthesis', 'To explain the process and factors affecting photosynthesis', 'To compare different types of plants', 'To discuss the evolution of chloroplasts', 'b'),
