('reading', NULL, 71, 'Passage 8:\n\nThe development of writing systems represents one of humanity''s most significant intellectual achievements. The earliest known writing system, cuneiform, emerged in Mesopotamia around 3200 BCE. Initially, cuneiform used pictographic symbols to represent objects and concepts, but it gradually evolved into a more abstract system where symbols represented sounds or syllables.\n\nAround the same time, hieroglyphics developed in ancient Egypt. This writing system combined logographic and alphabetic elements, using pictures to represent words, sounds, or ideas. Hieroglyphics remained in use for over 3,000 years and was employed primarily for religious texts and monumental inscriptions.\n\nThe Phoenician alphabet, developed around 1050 BCE, marked a revolutionary change in writing. Unlike earlier systems that required hundreds or thousands of symbols, the Phoenician alphabet used only 22 characters to represent consonant sounds. This simplicity made literacy much more accessible. The Phoenician alphabet became the ancestor of most modern alphabetic systems, including Greek, Latin, and eventually the English alphabet.\n\nThe invention of writing had profound effects on human civilization. It enabled the preservation of knowledge across generations, facilitated the administration of complex societies, and allowed for the development of literature and recorded history. Without writing, the accumulated knowledge and culture that define modern civilization would not exist.\n\nWhat is the main topic of the passage?', 'The invention of cuneiform', 'Ancient Egyptian culture', 'The development and importance of writing systems', 'The Phoenician civilization', 'c'),
