('reading', NULL, 91, 'Passage 10:\n\nThe human brain is arguably the most complex organ in the body, containing approximately 86 billion neurons that communicate through trillions of synaptic connections. These neurons form intricate networks that enable all aspects of human cognition, from basic sensory processing to abstract reasoning and creative thought.\n\nThe brain is divided into several distinct regions, each with specialized functions. The cerebral cortex, the brain''s outer layer, is responsible for higher-order thinking, including language, decision-making, and problem-solving. The limbic system, located deeper in the brain, plays a crucial role in emotion and memory formation. The cerebellum, positioned at the back of the brain, coordinates movement and balance.\n\nOne of the brain''s most remarkable features is its plasticity—the ability to reorganize and form new neural connections throughout life. This neuroplasticity allows the brain to adapt to new experiences, learn new skills, and even recover from injuries. Research has shown that learning a new language, musical instrument, or other complex skill can create new neural pathways and strengthen existing ones.\n\nDespite decades of research, many aspects of brain function remain mysterious. Scientists are still working to understand consciousness, the nature of memory storage, and how the brain generates subjective experiences. Advanced imaging technologies, such as functional MRI and PET scans, are providing new insights, but the brain continues to challenge our understanding.\n\nWhat is the main topic of the passage?', 'The number of neurons in the brain', 'The structure, functions, and mysteries of the human brain', 'How to improve brain function', 'The history of brain research', 'b'),
