('reading', NULL, 151, 'Passage 16:\n\nMemory is the cognitive process by which information is encoded, stored, and retrieved. Psychologists generally divide memory into three main types: sensory memory, short-term memory, and long-term memory. Each type plays a distinct role in how we process and retain information.\n\nSensory memory holds information from our senses for a very brief period, typically less than a second. This allows us to retain impressions of sensory information after the original stimulus has ceased. Short-term memory, also called working memory, can hold a limited amount of information (usually about 7 items) for approximately 20-30 seconds. This is the type of memory we use when remembering a phone number long enough to dial it.\n\nLong-term memory has a much larger capacity and can store information for extended periods, from days to a lifetime. Long-term memory is further divided into explicit memory (conscious memories of facts and events) and implicit memory (unconscious memories such as skills and habits). The process of transferring information from short-term to long-term memory is called consolidation, and it is strengthened through repetition and meaningful association.\n\nSeveral factors can affect memory performance. Sleep plays a crucial role in memory consolidation. Stress and anxiety can impair memory formation and retrieval. Age-related changes in the brain can affect memory, though normal aging does not necessarily lead to severe memory loss. Techniques such as mnemonics, visualization, and spacing out study sessions can improve memory retention.\n\nWhat is the main purpose of the passage?', 'To discuss memory disorders', 'To explain the types of memory and factors affecting it', 'To teach memory improvement techniques', 'To describe brain anatomy', 'b'),
