-- PASSAGE 18: Ocean Currents (Questions 171-180)
('reading', NULL, 171, 'Passage 18:\n\nOcean currents are continuous, directed movements of seawater generated by forces acting upon the water, including wind, the Coriolis effect, temperature and salinity differences, and tides. These currents play a vital role in regulating global climate by redistributing heat from the equator toward the poles. Understanding ocean currents is essential for predicting weather patterns, navigation, and studying marine ecosystems.\n\nSurface currents, which affect the upper 400 meters of the ocean, are primarily driven by wind. The Gulf Stream, for example, is a powerful warm current that originates in the Gulf of Mexico and flows along the eastern coast of the United States before crossing the Atlantic toward Europe. This current significantly moderates the climate of Western Europe, making it much warmer than other regions at similar latitudes.\n\nDeep ocean currents, also known as thermohaline circulation, are driven by differences in water density, which is affected by temperature (thermo) and salinity (haline). Cold, salty water is denser and sinks, while warm, less salty water rises. This creates a global "conveyor belt" of water that circulates slowly throughout the world''s oceans, taking hundreds or thousands of years to complete a full cycle.\n\nClimate change poses potential threats to ocean currents. As polar ice melts, it adds fresh water to the ocean, which could disrupt the density-driven currents. Changes in ocean currents could have far-reaching effects on climate patterns, marine life, and human societies that depend on stable climatic conditions.\n\nWhat is the main idea of the passage?', 'How to navigate using ocean currents', 'The role and types of ocean currents and threats to them', 'The history of oceanography', 'Marine life in the ocean', 'b'),
